### 2. Cache key for @Cacheable uses pageNumber only, not pageSize or sort:
```java
@Cacheable(value = "recommendations", key = "#userId + ':' + #pageable.pageNumber")
```
If two requests come with the same userId and pageNumber but different pageSize or sort, they would return the same cached result.

### 3. @CacheEvict on generateRecommendation uses key with allEntries=true PLUS a key expression:
```java
@CacheEvict(value = "recommendations", key = "#trigger.userId + ':*'", allEntries = true)
```
When allEntries=true, the key attribute is ignored. So this evicts ALL entries in the "recommendations" cache, not just the ones for this user.

### 4. AuthServiceClient is injected but never called in any visible service:
```java
@Component
public class AuthServiceClient {
    public UserProfileDTO getUserProfile(Long id) {
        return restClient.get()
                .uri("/auth/users/{id}", id)
                .retrieve()
                .body(UserProfileDTO.class);
    }
}
```

### 5. SecurityConfig uses jwt() with empty lambda:
```java
.oauth2ResourceServer(oauth2 ->
    oauth2.jwt(jwt -> {})
);
```
The JWT decoder is configured purely via application.properties:
```
spring.security.oauth2.resourceserver.jwt.jwk-set-uri=${auth.service.url}/.well-known/jwks.json
```
The `${auth.service.url}` in jwk-set-uri references another property. In Spring Boot, property-in-property expansion is supported, but only if `auth.service.url` is resolved at that point.

