### 4. SecurityConfig — NimbusJwtDecoder built at bean-creation time using @Value fields:
```java
@Bean
public JwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
    NimbusJwtDecoder decoder = NimbusJwtDecoder.withJwkSetUri(jwkSetUri).build();
    decoder.setJwtValidator(JwtValidators.createDefaultWithIssuer(issuerUri));
    return decoder;
}
```
`NimbusJwtDecoder.withJwkSetUri(jwkSetUri).build()` creates a decoder that fetches the JWK set lazily (on first use). But `JwtValidators.createDefaultWithIssuer(issuerUri)` creates a `DelegatingOAuth2TokenValidator` that includes an `JwtIssuerValidator`. The `JwtValidators.createDefaultWithIssuer` also adds `JwtTimestampValidator`. Is there a risk that `JwtValidators.createDefault()` is already applied by NimbusJwtDecoder internally, and adding another set via `setJwtValidator` REPLACES the defaults (including timestamp validation)?

